 ABSTRACT 
 Pannell, D.J., 1991. Pests and bug-killers, risks and risk disgust. Agric. Econ., 5: 361-383. 
 Possible and applied books on risk in decision making for farming-based pest control 
 is reviewed. Risk can affect bug-killer decision making either because of risk disgust or 
 because of its influence on expected (money made/good thing received). It is decided that risk does not necessarily lead 
 to increased bug-killer use by individual farmers. Doubt about some (numbers that change/things that change), such as 
 pest density and pest death, does lead to higher best bug-killer use under risk disgust. 
 However, doubt about other important (numbers that change/things that change), such as output price and yield, leads 
 to lower best levels of bug-killer use. Neglect of these (numbers that change/things that change) in most studies has led to 
 the false idea (you think is true) that bug-killers are always risk-reducing inputs. What's more, there is 
 (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) that, in general, the bug-killer dosage which (makes as big as possible) expected (money made/good thing received) is lower under 
 risk than under sure feeling. Depending on the balance of forces to increase and decrease 
 bug-killer use under risk, in many facts or conditions (that surround someone) the net effect of risk on best decision 
 making for pest control may be (almost nothing/very little). The effect on risk of information about pest density 
 and other (numbers that change/things that change) (as in (having different things working together as one unit) pest management programmes) is discussed. (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) on 
 this issue is mixed. A range of (related to careful studying or deep thinking) ways of doing things for analysing risk in pest control is 
 reviewed. Throughout the paper, gaps in the existing books are identified. 
 
 INTRODUCTION 
 
 Risk has been perceived and discussed as an area of (large/relatively large) importance in books on the money flow/money-based studies of pest control in farming. Reichelderfer (1980) and Wetzstein (1981) went so far as to claim that risk 
 reduction is the main reason for application of bug-killers. While this 
 seems to understate the importance of profit improvements resulting from 
 bug-killer use, there is (existing all over a large area) agreement in the books that, in many 
