 facts or conditions (that surround someone), risk (things to carefully think about) influence bug-killer use (e.g. Carlson and 
 Main, 1976; Conway, 1977; Reichelderfer and Bottrell, 1985; Antle and 
 Capalbo, 1986; Lichtenberg and Zilberman, 1986a). 
 The aim of this paper is to review the books on the hit/effect of risk and 
 risk disgust on decisions to control farming-based pests by use of 
 chemical bug-killers. Some clearly stated/particular issues are talked about including: the 
 hit/effect of risk on control decisions by risk-neutral decision makers, the 
 hit/effect of risk disgust on pest control decisions, the effect of risk on the 
 level of bug-killer use, the effect of bug-killer use on the level of risk, the 
 hit/effect of information use on risk, which sources of risk may be important 
 in the bug-killer problem and whether these sources of risk have been 
 well enough thought about/believed in applied studies. In addition a range of methods for 
 examining risk in pest control decisions are reviewed and examples given 
 from the books. Parts of the topic which have been neglected in the books are identified. 
 A GENERAL RESPONSE MODEL FOR PESTICIDES 
 
 The reader may find it helpful in the course of the review to refer to a 
 simple model of yield response to bug-killer use. Lichtenberg and 
 Zilberman (1986b) showed that for money-based and (related to studying numbers) reasons it is 
 important to represent response to bug-killers as a two-stage process: bug-killers kill pests, and it is the reduction in pest levels which increases yield. 
 This way we have pest density (P) as a function of initial pest density (P0 ) and a 
 kill function which depends on the rate of chemical applied [K( C) is the 
 proportion of pests killed at chemical dose C]: 
 P = P0 [_( 1 - K (C)]_) 
 
 (1) 
 
 The kill function differs/changes for different pests and bug-killers and can depend on 
 timing and (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) conditions. Actual yield ( Y) is a function of 
 pest-free yield (Y0 ) and D(P), a damage function giving (fair in amount, related to something else/properly sized compared to something else) yield 
 loss at pest density P: 
 Y= Y0 [1- D(P)]_) 
 
 (2) 
 
 D(P) depends on a range of factors and differs/changes for different pests and 
 
 different crops or (areas of grassy land). Herbicides may also cause direct damage to the crop yield but for the purposes of this review, the simple two-equation 
 model will be enough: 
 (money made/good things received) ( 7T) are given by: 
 1r 
 
 = YPy - CPc -A - F 
 
 (3) 
 
 where PY is output price, Pc is chemical cost, A is chemical application costs 
 
 PESTS AND PESTICIDES, RISK AND RISK AVERSION 
 
 363 
 
 (which are usually independent of dosage) and F is other production 
 costs. 
 This simple model illustrates the major parts/pieces of the pest control 
 problem. It can be used as the basis for a range of different types of 
 analysis. For example it could be used to find the dividing line pest density 
 above which application of a fixed recommended chemical dosage would 
 produce benefits greater than costs. (first one, then the other) not important analysis could be 
 used to decide/figure out the best chemical dose. The analysis could be static or, 
 with added/more functions, energetic. 
 There are some limits/guidelines in the model which are likely to be 
 (random/including random data points). In equation (1), pest density may be uncertain as a result of 
 doubt about the first pest density, the proportion of pests killed or 
 the chemical dosage actually applied. In equation (2), yield will be uncertain 
 because of doubt about pest-free yield, the level of damage and the final 
 pest density. (money made/good things received) in equation (3) are most likely to be affected by 
 variance in produce and output price. The model illustrates the way these 
 different sources of doubt affect the variance of income. For example, 
 doubt about the level of pest death leads to doubt about pest 
 density which in turn affects (fair in amount, related to something else/properly sized compared to something else) yield loss, actual produce and, 
 finally, (money made/good things received). The different sources of doubt will be discussed further 
 in the review. 
 THEORETICAL FRAMEWORKS FOR ANALYSIS OF RISK 
 
 Although the first (book, magazine, etc.) on risk in pest management used the 
 idea  of "degree of possible surprise" (Hillebrant, 1960), the most in control/most common 
 way of thinking for risk analysis in money flow/money-based studies has been expected utility (biggest increase/best possible extent) (e.g. Anderson et al., 1977). In response to (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) that many people 
 in a planned way violate (statements about the future) of expected utility explanation (e.g. Allais, 1953; 
 MacCrimmon and Larsson, 1979) there has been a recent growth of more 
 'generalised' versions of the explanation (e.g. Machina, 1982; Quiggin, 1982; 
 Chew, 1983). However there have, up until now, been no applications of any of the 
 generalized utility explanations to problems of pest control. Of the studies 
 reviewed in this paper, those which account for risk disgust think about/believe the 
 decision maker's goal to be expected utility (biggest increase/best possible extent) or, in a 
 couple of cases, maximin ((biggest increase/best possible extent) of the minimum return). It seems 
 likely that, so long as the chance distribution of net returns is not 
 very much skewed, expected utility (biggest increase/best possible extent) will (well enough/good enough/in a smart way) come close to the more general explanations (Quiggin and Fisher, 1989). 
 Although the studies reviewed here are all concerned with risk, they change/differ 
 widely in many respects. The assumed goal of decision makers ranges 
 from expected profit (biggest increase/best possible extent) through expected utility (biggest increase/best possible extent) to 
 
 364 
 
