 the extreme degree of risk disgust suggested by the maxnmn way of thinking/basic truth/rule. 
 Different studies treat different limits/guidelines of the pest/pesticide/ crop 
 system as being uncertain. There has been a range of (related to careful studying or deep thinking) (solid basic structures on which bigger things can be built) 
 employed including energetic programming (DP), Bayesian decision explanation 
 and (random/including random data points) (wasting very little while working or producing something). The following discussion describes these 
 differences and reviews particular studies. 
 RISK NEUTRALITY VERSUS RISK A VERSION 
 
 The broadest labeling of the risk books is into those studies 
 which assume risk neutrality and those assuming risk disgust. The idea (you think is true) of risk neutrality is often made for the purposes of simpleness and 
 (ability to be managed or controlled) (e.g. Marra and Carlson, 1983; Moffitt et al., 1984; Taylor and 
 Burt, 1984; Gold and Sutton, 1986; Johnston and Price, 1986; Zacharias et 
 al., 1986). The first part of this discussion thinks about/believes the truth/trueness of this 
 idea (you think is true). Given the extreme statements made by some authors about the 
 importance of risk disgust as the most important reason for damage control, it 
 may seem that the idea (you think is true) of risk neutrality is wrong. However, 
 there have been studies which found that risk disgust had (almost nothing/very little) hit/effect 
 on decision making for pest control. Webster (1977) found that for a 
 fungus-killer-spraying problem in the United Kingdom, the decision of whether 
 or not to spray was very insensitive to the degree of risk disgust. Only 
 people with extreme decision judging requirements, such as maximin, would (change to make better/change to fit new conditions) 
 their spraying decision in response to risk. No farmers in a sample of 29 
 were found to be this (not wanting to do anything dangerous). 
 (in almost the same way), Thornton (1984) found that decisions on control of a fungal 
 disease of grain in New Zealand were almost unaffected by risk disgust. 
 In many tests of disease widespread diseases, differences in recommendation 
 between expected (money made/good thing received) and expected utility (biggest increase/best possible extent) happened with a 
 frequency of about 0.03. 
 Finally, Pannell (1990a) found that when a range of sources of doubt was carefully thought about/believed, the variance of income was almost unchanged over a 
 wide range of herbicide dosages. This points to/shows that the best herbicide 
 dosage would not be greatly affected by risk disgust. 
 In addition to these indications that risk disgust may have little hit/effect 
 on pest control decisions, there is also (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) that many farmers are 
 about risk-neutral or only (a) little (not wanting to do anything dangerous) (e.g. Bond and 
 Wonder, 1980; Poetsley and Harris, 1987). Finally, Carlson (1984) and 
 Musser et al. (1986) have suggested that risk may not be an important 
 (serious thought/something to think about/respect) in farmers' decisions on pest control. Taken together, these 
 studies appear to provide some support for use of a risk-neutral (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built). 
 However there are reasons to question the general (ability to be used for something) of the results 
 
