 to changes in all limits/guidelines, including risk disgust, would increase. Webster (1977) also used a binary decision rule. The scale of the problem 
 analysed by Webster was not reported in the article. 
 In addition to these reasons for questioning the ends/end results of Webster 
 and Thornton, there are reasons for caution in the (understanding/ explanation) of studies 
 which find a low average level of risk disgust. There is large amounts of 
 difference/different version in the degree of risk disgust and a big number of farmers 
 are highly (not wanting to do anything dangerous) (Bond and Wonder, 1980; Hamal and Anderson, 
 1982). 
 Finally, some authors have reported finding that risk disgust does 
