 Pingali and Carlson, 1985). However the strength of this end/end result should 
 not be overstated. Underground tunnels (1983) managed and did/done an econometric study to 
 decide/figure out which (numbers that change/things that change) influence demand for bug-killers. In the guess, the degree of producers' hatred of risk was represented by a very 
 (very simple/rough and rude) (substitute-related) (number or thing that changes): the ratio of areas of land planted in obey total areas of land. 
 Ends/end results about risk based on this (number or thing that changes) should be very uncertain/not definite. In 
 another moving backward study, Pingali and Carlson (1985) found that the level of 
 bug-killers used was positively related to the variance of damage. Although 
 they attributed this to risk disgust on the part of decision makers, the 
 
