 Risk neutrality 
 Of those studies in which risk neutrality has been assumed, the majority 
 have been based on a pre-decided decision (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built) [e.g. most of the 
 studies referred to in (book lists) by McCarl (1981) and Osteen et al. (1981)]_). 
 This approach can sometimes be defended on the basis that in a strictly 
 linear model, the decision which (makes as big as possible) expected (money made/good thing received) in a (random/including random data points) 
 (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built) goes along with the (money made/good thing received) making the most of decision in a pre-decided 
 (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built) using expected values of limits/guidelines. This hints that if expected profit (biggest increase/best possible extent) is assumed, including (random/including random data points) limits/guidelines in a linear model introduces unnecessary complex difficulty to the analysis 
 without affecting results. Such was the case in studies by Marra and Carlson 
 (1983) and Marra et al. (1989). They clearly included a separate chance distribution for the length of the spraying period, but this was unnecessary since all non-linear relationships in the model were came close to by 
 linear functions. 
 Anyway there are a few ways in which risk can affect the decisions 
 of people whose goal is to (make as big as possible) expected (money made/good thing received). Tisdell (1986) 
 showed that doubt about a limit/guideline value can affect the best level 
 of pest control by affecting expected (money made/good thing received). He argued that 
 "in many cases the expected level of application is greater under doubt than under 
 full information but ... this depends on curviness conditions of (connected/related) functions" (p.161). 
 
 and that 
 "curviness conditions may sometimes be such as to give rise to the opposite result" 
 (p.159). 
 
 He did not discuss which limits/guidelines are likely to increase and which to 
 decrease treatment levels under doubt. Auld and Tisdell (1986, 1987, 
 1988) showed that because of curviness of the relationship between weed 
 density and crop yield, doubt about weed density reduces expected 
 yield loss. Auld and Tisdell (1987) argued (but did not prove) that this 
 increases the money-based dividing line, reducing the overall level of bug-killer use. 
 They noted that this does not seem agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with comments in the 
 
