 They found modest support for the guess, with very small differences 
 between the results of their pre-decided and (random/including random data points) models. 
 A third possibility is where the decision maker is subject to a progressive 
 not important taxation rate. Taylor (1986) showed that the effect of this on 
 decision making is mostly the same as the effect of risk disgust; it 
 makes the decision maker behave in an (based on what's seen or what seems obvious) more (not wanting to do anything dangerous) manner 
 than would otherwise be the case. 
 Risk disgust 
 This section of the review examines the widely accepted views that risk 
 increases bug-killer usage and that bug-killer usage reduces risk. The importance of risk as a (thing that decides something) of bug-killer usage has been focused in the 
 books with the most in control/most common view being that bug-killer use reduces risk so 
 that if risk is included in a model, risk disgust will cause the best 
 treatment rate to be increased. This is in contrast to other types of inputs, 
 such as (material that makes plants grow better)s, which are usually supposed to be used at lower levels 
 under risk disgust than under risk neutrality. Feder (1979) is commonly 
 referred to as having established the possible basis for the assumed positive 
 relationship between degree of risk and level of bug-killer usage. Feder 
 showed that under risk disgust, doubt about the level of pest (fill with lots of something harmful or disgusting)a- 
 
