 tion increases the best level of bug-killer use. However, crop damage was 
 came close to by a linear function, so the effect of doubt about pest 
 density on expected (money made/good thing received) (see above) was not thought about/believed. Auld and Tisdell 
 (1987) showed that, at least for weeds, doubt about pest density 
 reduces expected yield loss, and argued that this reduces the chance of 
 treatment being gave a reason for. This effect at least partially offsets the positive 
 effect of risk disgust on chemical usage. 
 Moffitt (1986) in his extension of the M-dividing line idea (Moffitt et al., 
 1984) to allow for risk disgust, further questions the accepted wisdom of 
 greater risk leading to greater bug-killer usage. He showed in his possible 
 model that, under risk, a higher dosage can be more than offset by less 
 frequent use (i.e. a higher dividing line) although this was not found to happen in 
 an scientific (online or paper form that asks for a job, money, admission, etc.) of the approach by Osteen et al. (1988). 
 A further (connected/related) issue which has received almost no comment in the 
 books is the fact that the reputation of bug-killers as "risk reducing 
 inputs" (Carlson, 1984; Robison and Barry, 1987) appears to be mainly 
 based on analyses which only think about/believe doubt about the level of pest 
 (situation where something is filled with lots of something harmful or disgusting) or chemical effectiveness (e.g. Feder, 1979; Robison and Barry, 1987; 
 Osteen et al., 1988). However, there are many other sources of doubt in the pest/pesticide/ crop system which may or may not result in 
 reduced risk as bug-killers are increased. Feder (1979) did think about/believe doubt about bug-killer effectiveness but was confusing about its hit/effect on 
 bug-killer usage. Chisaka (1977) showed that the level of crop yield loss 
 caused by weeds can be a significant source of doubt. Auld and Tisdell 
 (1987) thought about/believed doubt about crop yield loss in a risk-neutral setting, 
 finding that it would not affect decision making. They did not think about/believe its 
 effect on a (not wanting to do anything dangerous) decision maker. Robison and Barry (1987) commented in passing that the Feder model could be expanded to allow for 
 doubt about output price. They watched/followed that 
 "two random (numbers that change/things that change), however, quickly complicate our analysis, forcing us into number-based rather than (related to careful studying or deep thinking) approaches. What's more, we could find the dividing line level for 
 N * as before but the solution would require solving a quadratic formula with few 
 pre-decided results" (p.llO). 
 
 This may explain some of the shyness of most analysts to think about 
 uncertainties other than pest density. However this shyness may have 
 resulted in the continuing of a general false impression that bug-killers 
 always reduce risk. Pannell (1990a) found that for weeds, doubt about 
 output price, weed-free yield or chemical damage to the crop leads to greater 
 variance of income at higher herbicide rates. In many (surrounding conditions) these 
 may be more important sources of doubt than are pest density, pest 
 damage to crops or bug-killer effectiveness. In all (surrounding conditions), the question 
 of whether bug-killer use results in higher or lower income (quality of changing over time or at different places) 
 
