 depends on the balance of forces of positive and negative effects on risk. 
 Bug-killer usage will result in risk being increased in some situations and 
 reduced in others. In an analysis of ryegrass control in wheat in Western 
 Australia, Pannell (1990a) found that the forces balanced so that income 
 (quality of changing over time or at different places) was almost unchanged over a wide range of herbicide rates. 
 Some other authors have thought about/believed many sources of risk. 
 While they have not gave/given (related to careful studying or deep thinking) proof, they have produced some 
 support for the suggestion/possible plan that bug-killers do not always reduce risk. 
 Hawkins et al. (1977) managed and did/done money-planning analysis of field results from 
 weed control trials. These would have completely/in a hinting way included a few (related to the body function of living things) 
 sources of risk including weed density, herbicide effectiveness and weed-free 
 yield. They found that herbicide use increased the standard moving away of 
 returns, which hints that weed-free yield was the major source of (quality of changing over time or at different places) in the trials. 
 In studies by Cochran et al. (1985) and Greene et al. (1985), (testing out) 
 approaches were used to guess chance distributions of income for 
 analysis using (random/including random data points) control ways of doing things. The uncertain (numbers that change/things that change) 
 thought about/believed by Greene et al. (1985) were wheat yield, wheat price, soybean 
 price, July temperature and August rainfall. They assumed that these (numbers that change/things that change) followed a multivariate (usual/ commonly and regular/ healthy) distribution which was guessed from 
 20 years of historical data. Cochran et al. (1985) allowed for doubt 
 about the weather, yield, prices, the desire/decision of (situation where something is filled with lots of something harmful or disgusting) periods and 
 the calculation of yield loss. It is very interesting that in both these studies, 
 integrated pest management (IPM) plans, which generally involve reduced bug-killer use, were found to be (producing a lot with very little waste) for (not wanting to do anything dangerous) decision 
 makers. In the Greene et al. study, IPM plans clearly ruled 
 ordinary plans for even the highest level of risk disgust thought about/believed. 
 If bug-killer use did reduce risk, one might have expected (not wanting to do anything dangerous) decision 
 makers to prefer prophylactic bug-killer use. Cochran et al. (1985) used a 
 number of (random/including random data points) control judging requirements with different powers of (unfair treatment based on skin color, age, etc.). IPM plans were part of the (producing a lot with very little waste) set under all judging requirements. As the 
 judging requirement was made more discriminating, plans involving calendar spraying (i.e. pre-planned (disease-preventing treatment)s) were removed from the 
 (producing a lot with very little waste) set until the most discriminating judging requirement resulted in a (like nothing else) 
 ranking with IPM as the only (producing a lot with very little waste) plan. Again, if bug-killers were 
 risk-reducing, IPM plans involving lower bug-killer use might involve 
 higher risk and not be clearly (producing a lot with very little waste) for (not wanting to do anything dangerous) decision makers. 
 While these described/explained studies are interesting that bug-killers may not reduce 
 risk, there is a need for caution in crediting this (understanding/ explanation) to the results. 
 It may be that the use of information in IPM plans is itself risk-reducing. (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) in support of this is given by Antle (1988a) who found that 
 bug-killers used in an IPM programme were more risk-reducing than those 
 
