 used prophylactically. He also found that the value of information use in 
 IPM plans was (in a big way) higher for more (not wanting to do anything dangerous) decision makers. 
 Even if lower bug-killer use increases risk, information may be (good or well enough) 
 risk-reducing to more than offset this, making the IPM plan attractive to 
 (not wanting to do anything dangerous) decision makers. Anyway it does appear that the risk-reducing nature of bug-killers is by no means proven. This is an issue deserving 
 further attention. 
 Finally, note that even if bug-killer uses do reduce income risk, it 
 does not necessarily follow that a (random/including random data points) decision model will lead to 
 greater bug-killer usage than will a pre-decided model. As discussed earlier, 
 the introduction of risk into the decision process may affect expected (money made/good thing received) 
 in such a way that chemical use tends to be reduced. In some situations 
 this effect may more than offset increases in chemical usage due to risk 
 promisesiOn. 
 The rest of the paper is a review of applied studies which have 
 allowed for risk. The different ways of doing things which have been used are described. 
 Advantages and disadvantages of the ways of doing things are suggested. 
 BAYESIAN DECISION THEORY 
 
 Bayesian decision explanation is concerned with the rewriting/redoing of risky decisions 
 in response to information about the (problem that is important now). Many Bayesian 
 studies calculate the expected value of information to be used in a decision. 
 Anderson et al. (1977) described the use of Bayesian decision 
 explanation to a range of problem types in farming. One of the earliest 
 applications of the approach to damage control was by Carlson (1970) who 
 examined the disease control practices of Californian peach growers. He 
 brought out prior chance distributions of disease loss from growers and used 
 these to show that if the number of applications of chemicals is well 
 (changed to make better/changed to fit new conditions) in response to disease forecasts, chemical usage can be (in a big way) 
 reduced. 
 Webster (1977) managed and did/done a Bayesian analysis of a fungal (something that feeds off of, and weakens, something else) problem on wheat. He brought out (quadratic) utility functions from farmers and, as 
 discussed earlier, found that the decision of whether to spray was very 
 insensitive to risk attitudes. In a follow-up study, Menz and Webster (1981) 
 used a Bayesian approach to guess the expected value of information 
 which would be given by a possible (like a recommendation, but not an order) big plan/layout/dishonest plan proposed by 
 Webster (1977). They found that the expected value of information was very 
 high so that benefits of the proposed big plan/layout/dishonest plan would be very likely to 
 outweigh costs. In a later (book, magazine, etc.), Webster (1982) gave a general 
 discussion of the value of information in pest control and presented examples for a disease control program. The analysis was simplified by assuming 
 
 PESTS AND PESTICIDES. RISK AND RISK AVERSION 
 
 371 
 
 expected profit (biggest increase/best possible extent) and by assuming that the values of different 
 types of information are (serving to add something) and independent. 
 Mumford (1981) focused the (not definite) parts of pest control decisions. He found that pest control decisions by members of a particular 
 group of surveyed farmers was agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with a simple Bayesian model in 
 their pest control behaviour. He assumed that the goal of the more 
 (not wanting to do anything dangerous) farmers in the group came close to to 'maximin', although 
 Webster (1977) found no farmers in a group of 29 who were that (not wanting to do anything dangerous). 
 Thornton and Dent (1984a, b) focused on rewriting/redoing of best disease 
 control plans in response to information on climate and disease information levels. They described their approach as "completely/in a hinting way Bayesian" (Thornton and Dent, 1984a, p.123) and presented a (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built) for putting into use it 
 for use by farmers. They found that the expected value of climate and 
 disease level information "increases with decreasing partial risk disgust, 
 since the value is dependent on the recommendation not to spray, (not wanting to do anything dangerous) 
 people being unwilling not to apply spray" (Thornton and Dent, 1984b, 
 p.241). 
 The study by Antle (1988a, b) might also be thought about/believed as "completely/in a hinting way 
 Bayesian" in its focus on risk and (one after the other) decision making. Interestingly, in a case study of IPM plans for tomato production, he received/got 
 the opposite result to Thornton and Dent (1984b); greater degrees of risk 
 disgust were connected with (in a big way) higher values of information. 
 Another interesting finding was that although insecticides as a group were 
 found to be (only a little bit) risk-reducing inputs, those bug-killers applied with 
 (compared to other things) low frequency in the IPM programme were found to be much more risk-reducing than those applied prophylactically. Clearly the 
 degree of risk reduction received/got from bug-killer use depends not just on the 
 level of bug-killer used, but also on the way it is used. Antle's finding 
 hints that information which aids in deciding/figuring out best bug-killer use 
 may be more risk reducing than bug-killers (by itself/in and of itself). 
 Moffitt et al. (1986) examined the value of publicly given information 
 on pest levels in a situation where private scouting services were available. 
 They found that the value depended on the reliability of public information. 
 If it were (a) little less reliable than private information, public information 
 still had a positive net value to farmers because of its lower cost. However, 
 below a certain level of reliability, public information had no value. 
 Stefanou et al. (1986) presented a Bayesian model including decisions 
 on both whether to scout and whether to spray. They applied the model to 
 cotton lygus bug in California and managed and did/done wide-ranging sensitivity analySIS. 
 
 The studies discussed above all allowed for risk disgust on the part of 
 decision makers. Bayesian decision explanation can also be applied in a risk-neu- 
 
 372 
 
 D.J. PANNELL 
 
 tral setting. For example Johnston and Price (1986) assumed risk neutrality 
 in calculating the expected values of perfect and (not totally pure/not totally correct) information in 
 the problem of stored grain insect control. Cammell and Way (1977) applied 
 a risk-neutral Bayesian model to guess the value of forecasting black bean 
 small, plant-damaging bug (groups of people/animals/things). They found that basing treatment decisions on this 
 information was much more money-making than (usually done) treatment or no 
 treatment. 
 All of the farm level studies referred to in this section treat the bug-killer as a 
 binary (number or thing that changes) to be applied at the recommended rate or not at all. There 
 does not seem to have been an use of Bayesian decision explanation in 
 which treatment dosage has been treated as a continuous (number or thing that changes). It is also 
 important/famous that none of these studies examine a problem of weed control. It 
 appears that a Bayesian approach to chance rewriting/redoing is highly related 
 to problems of strategical weed control. 
 STOCHASTIC EFFICIENCY 
 
 In the Bayesian studies described above, particular utility functions were 
 brought out or assumed for use in the analysis. If a specific utility function is 
 used then it is possible to give an clear ranking of all plans 
 (being thought about carefully). However, these rankings are not necessarily consistent 
 with the preferences of people who do not have the exact utility 
 function used in the analysis. 
 (random/including random data points) (wasting very little while working or producing something) analysis is used to create information which is 
 related to broadly defined groups of decision makers. There are a 
 number of different (random/including random data points) (wasting very little while working or producing something) judging requirements used depending on how 
 broadly defined a group of decision makers is being targeted: 
 (a) first-degree (random/including random data points) control (FSD) applies to all decision makers 
 who prefer more income to less (Strange quality and Saposnik, 1962); 
 (b) second-degree (random/including random data points) control (SSD) applies to those decision 
 makers from (a) who are (not wanting to do anything dangerous) (Hadar and Russell, 1969); 
 (c) third degree (random/including random data points) control (TSD) applies to those decision 
 makers from (b) whose degree of risk disgust decreases with increasing 
 wealth (Whitmore, 1970); 
 (d) (random/including random data points) control with respect to a function (SDWRF) is related 
 to decision makers whose degree of risk disgust lies between that of two 
 given utility functions. The width of the decision group can be varied 
 by (changing to make better/changing to fit new conditions) the functions which define the bounds (Meyer, 1977a, b). 
 The greater (statement that's not detailed) of these ways of doing things is only received/got at the cost of 
 reduced level of detail of their recommendations. In general they do not provide 
 a (like nothing else) ranking of the available plans. Rather they identify groups of 
 plans which are 'efficient'. All elements of the (producing a lot with very little waste) set of plans 
 
 PESTS AND PESTICIDES, RISK AND RISK AVERSION 
 
 373 
 
 would be preferred to all plans not in the (producing a lot with very little waste) set by all members of 
 the (connected/related) group of decision makers. A possible problem with the way of doing things is that the (producing a lot with very little waste) set can be change/differ  large, sometimes including most 
 of the available plan options. In this situation the information 
 given by the way of doing things is of little value. Greater (treating certain groups of people unfairly) power 
 can be gotten by more closely defining the group of decision makers (e.g. 
 using third degree, rather than second degree, (random/including random data points) control) andjor 
 by using ways of doing things such as curving out set (random/including random data points) control (Cochran et al., 
 1985). However, as Tolley and Pope (1988) watched/followed, "second degree 
 (random/including random data points) control has been easily implementable and continues to have a 
 famous place in (wasting very little while working or producing something) analysis" (p.694). Tolley and Pope noted that 
 sampling errors in the guess of chance distribution functions are 
 usually not thought about/believed. They showed that if sampling errors are carefully thought about/believed, 
 the size of the (producing a lot with very little waste) set is increased even further. 
 Finally in this background information on (random/including random data points) (wasting very little while working or producing something), it should 
 be noted that a very common method of identifying (producing a lot with very little waste) plans for 
 (not wanting to do anything dangerous) decision makers is E-V analysis (Markowitz, 1952). However E-V 
 analysis has been widely criticised because it has very strong needed things 
 for truth/trueness (Lambert and McCarl, 1985). Either returns must be distributed 
 (usually/ in a common and regular way) or the decision maker must have a quadratic utility function. The 
 former is often not the case and the last thing just mentioned is generally dismissed as 
 silly because it hints increasing risk disgust with increasing wealth. 
 The books on the money flow/money-based studies of pest control includes five applications 
 of (random/including random data points) control: two in problems of insect control, one on a disease 
 problem, one on weeds and one including weed, pest and disease 
 control. Between them, these studies have included most of the (wasting very little while working or producing something) 
 judging requirements described above (all except TSD). 
 Papers by Greene et al. (1985) and Cochran et al. (1985) were described 
 above in the discussion of whether bug-killers are risk-reducing inputs. 
 Greene et al. (1985) used SDWRF to rank different plans for insect pest 
 control in soybeans. They found that IPM plans are (producing a lot with very little waste) relative to 
 prophylactic spraying for a wide range of risk attitudes. Cochran et al. 
 (1985) used FSD, SSD, SDWRF and SDWRF with curving out set (random/including random data points) 
 control to test plans for Apple scab control. Again IPM plans were favoured. 
 Moffitt et al. (1983) used FSD and SSD to test a range of other choice 
 citrus thrip control methods for inland Southern California orange groves. 
 Of the eight plans thought about/believed, six were in the FSD (producing a lot with very little waste) set while 
 three were in the SSD (producing a lot with very little waste) set. 
 Zacharias and Grube (1984) examined a range of crop rotations in 
 conjunction with different weed control methods. They used SDWRF to 
 examine plan rankings for (not wanting to do anything dangerous), risk-neutral and risk-preferring 
 
 374 
 
 D.J. PANNELL 
 
 decision makers. Their ends/end results about the effect on risk of using information to (change to make better/change to fit new conditions) herbicide usage were the reverse of Antle's (1988a): 
 (one after the other) changing herbicides on a once-a-year basis as compared to applying a single major 
 herbicide was found to increase both net returns and risk" (p.l13). 
 
 Finally Musser et al. (1981) compared the results of E-V analysis and 
 FSD jSSD in ranking four sets of plans for controlling weeds, pests and 
 sicknesses in Georgia. They found that, in an E-V (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built), both ordinary plans and IPM plans were (producing a lot with very little waste). IPM had higher mean net 
 income but also higher variance of income and so was not clearly preferred 
 to ordinary control in an E-V (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built). However IPM was found to 
 be FSD over ordinary plans and so would be preferred by all 
 decision makers (without any concern about/having nothing to do with) their risk preferences. Note again that use of 
 an IPM plan was not found to reduce risk. (based on what's seen or what seems obvious) in both of these 
 studies, chemical sprays were risk-reducing and information was not (good or well enough) risk reducing to offset the increase in risk resulting from lower 
 chemical use. 
 Studies employing an E-V approach to testing-related risk in pest control have 
 included Carlson (1970), King et al. (1986) and Lybecker et al. (1988). 
 DYNAMIC PROGRAMMING 
 
 Pest control in a crop or (area of grassy land) may have either positive or negative 
 carry-over effects in later crops or (areas of grassy land). For example, one of the 
 advantages of including the (pea, bean, lentil, etc.) crop, lupins, in rotation with cereals in 
 Western Australia is that they allow use of the herbicide simazine for weed 
 control, reducing the costs of grass weed competition and control in later cereal crops. In general, the number of weed seeds with possible ability to 
 begin growing in a given year depends on the degree of control in previous years. 
 A negative effect of weed control in crops is that the density of later 
 (areas of grassy land) can be reduced. Pattern of behavior factors such as these may affect best 
 weed control practices. 
 A energetic (related to careful studying or deep thinking) (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built) is even more important for problems of 
 pest and disease control. Reproduction rates are very high for these organisms 
 so that (situation where something is filled with lots of something harmful or disgusting) levels can increase quickly. For most weeds, the life cycle 
 takes at least a year so that population patterns are not as very important to the 
 money-based problem as they are for pests and sicknesses. Ways of doing things used to 
 face/deal with energetic problems include (testing out) (discussed in the next section) 
 and DP. 
 Christine Shoemaker stands out as the major contributor to the books 
 in the DP field, especially for management of alfalfa weevil. In two of her 
 papers, (random/including random data points) DP was used to test the effect of risk on decision 
 making (Shoemaker and Onstad, 1983; Shoemaker, 1984). In Shoemaker 
 
 PESTS AND PESTICIDES, RISK AND RISK A VERSION 
 
 375 
 
 (1984) the issues of multiple bug-killer uses and carryover of bug-killer 
 from one season to the next were carefully thought about/believed. As well as using more than one 
 (number or thing that changes) to decide/figure out whether to treat, she has also thought about/believed more than 
 one type of treatment: bug-killer use and (related to the body function of living things) control (Shoemaker and Onstad, 1983). 
 Taylor and Burt (1984) used (random/including random data points) DP to decide/figure out whether or not to 
 spray andjor unplanted to control wild oats in spring wheat in the U.S.A. 
 Pandey (1989) used pre-decided and (random/including random data points) DP to decide/figure out best 
 herbicide rates for control of wild oats in Western Australia. 
 There has also been an application of (random/including random data points) DP to a problem of 
 disease control. Zacharias et al. (1986) used (random/including random data points) DP to test 
 management plans for controlling soybean body-lump-related nematode. They. tested 
 and supported/judged as correct Antle's (1983) guess that risk-neutral (i.e. expected profitmaximising) decision makers can respond to risk if the problem is energetic. 
 In each of these studies, expected profit (biggest increase/best possible extent) was assumed to be 
 the goal; there was no (money given/freedom to move) for risk disgust on the part of 
 decision makers. 
 The obvious advantage of DP as a solution method is its (producing a lot with very little waste) 
 handling of patterns. The main disadvantage is the 'curse of quality': as the number of state (numbers that change/things that change) in the model increases, the number of 
 calculations needed/demanded for solution increases (more and more as time goes on) and can become 
 (in a way that shows no common sense) large. Because of this DP generally needs/demands that complex systems be 
 greatly simplified before they can be analysed. 
 Another part/face  of DP which may be thought about/believed a disadvantage is that it 
 can only handle separate decision problems. Only separate other choice plans can be tested, not continuous (numbers that change/things that change) such as chemical dosage, 
 although this can be overcome to a degree by (thinking about/when one thinks about) a separate number 
 of chemical dosages as different plans (e.g. Pandey, 1989). 
 SIMULATION 
 
 (testing out) models of vanous kinds have been used in some 
 different ways to test the money flow/money-based studies of pest, disease or weed control. 
 Risk disgust has been analysed in some ways in these studies: by 
 number-based solution of the expected utility (biggest increase/best possible extent) problem (Lazarus 
 and Swanson, 1983; Thornton and Dent 1984a, b), by E-V analysis (King et 
 al., 1986) and by (random/including random data points) control approaches (Cochran et al., 1985; 
 Greene et al., 1985). 
 An advantage of (testing out) models is that they allow guess of 
 technical relationships which would be expensive, time-using/eating or silly/not doable to guess from field experiments. A second advantage is that, 
 relative to optimization ways of doing things such as DP or mathematical program- 
 
 376 
 
 D.J. PANNELL 
 
 ming, they allow more described/explained representation of (related to the body function of living things) and technical 
 parts/pieces of the system (Shoemaker, 1984). A disadvantage is that in most 
 money-based computer programs they must be solved many times to reach a 
 end/end result. For example, Shoemaker (1979) noted that to manage and do a almost the same 
 analysis to that carried out by a particular DP model, a (testing out) model 
 would have to be solved 1 380 000 times. (testing out) models do not suggest 
 use of a particular money-based (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built); rather they can be used to provide 
 inputs to money-based analyses of a few types. 
 There have been a few studies in which (testing out) models were used to 
 guess chance distributions of technical limits/guidelines which were then 
 used to guess dividing lines under risk. For example Thornton and Dent 
 (1984a; b) described the design, operation and (putting into) use of such a 
 system for testing control of the fungal disease Puccini a hordei in New 
 Zealand grain crops. The effect of (related to the Earth's weather) different version of the variance of 
 (money made/good thing received) was guessed by (testing out) and used to calculate dividing lines under 
 risk disgust. Their study was discussed earlier in the big picture  of Bayesian 
 decision explanation. King et al. (1986) guessed dividing lines for weed control in 
 continuous corn ( Zea mays). Although they did not think about/believe the hit/effect of 
 risk disgust on the decision, they guessed the variance of (money made/good thing received) for 
 different plans. Lazarus and Swanson (1983) did allow for risk disgust 
 in their test of rootworm control in corn. Although their representation of (related to the body function of living things) relationships was (compared to other things) overly-simple, this allowed them to 
 analyse a more complex decision problem. They guessed not just pest 
 dividing lines at which chemical application was (done for good reason), but also a higher 
 dividing line at which it was worth rotating to another crop. 
 A somewhat almost the same  use of (testing out) models has been to guess 
 chance distributions of net returns for test using (random/including random data points) control ways of doing things. Cochran et al. (1985) used this approach in their computer program of curving out set (random/including random data points) control to test of different apple scab 
 control plans, as did Greene et al. (1985) in their use of generalised 
 (random/including random data points) control to test soybean (combined different things together so they worked as one unit) pest management 
 plans. 
 ANALYTICAL/NUMERICAL APPROACHES 
 
 In some applied studies of risk in pest control, direct number-based 
 solution of possible models has been employed. Moffitt et al. (1984) 
 number-basedly solved for the best limits/guidelines of their M-dividing line model 
 for corn nematode control under doubt about pest density. Osteen et 
 al. (1988) managed and did/done a almost the same  study of corn nematode control which, unlike 
 Moffitt et al. (1984), allowed for risk disliking decision making. Liapis and 
 Moffitt (1983) used the huge utility moment creating function 
 
 PESTS AND PESTICIDES, RISK AND RISK AVERSION 
 
 377 
 
 approach to calculate sure feeling equals of different cotton pest control 
 plans under different degrees of risk disgust. The use of this approach 
 was attacked by Scott et al. (1986) but defended by Liapis and Moffitt 
 (1986). Lazarus and Swanson (1983) used number-based solution in conjunction 
 with a (testing out) model to calculate pest density dividing lines for application 
 of bug-killer and for switching crop rotation. 
 The number-based solution ways of doing things employed in these studies can be very 
 useful when the problem is not agreeable to (related to careful studying or deep thinking) solution or to 
 solution by common optimization ways of doing things such as DP or LP. This can be 
 the case, for example, when the profit function has more than one local 
 best, when it has a few state (numbers that change/things that change) or when close links with a 
 (testing out) model are desired. 
 In some studies clearly connected with or related to bug-killer use, Lichtenberg and 
 Zilberman have used not important analysis to get best legal/law-based standards for reducing the chance of negative effects on health (Lichtenberg 
 and Zilberman 1988a, 1988b; Lichtenberg et al. 1988). In each of these 
 analyses (money given/freedom to move) was made for "disgust to doubt." No other 
 studies of public or social pest control problems have thought about/believed risk except 
 by conducting sensitivity analysis (e.g. Pannell, 1984; Denne, 1988). 
 RELEVANCE FOR DEVELOPED AND DEVELOPING COUNTRIES 
 
 Almost all studies referred to in this review deal with problems in developed 
 countries. However the review also has relevance for developing countries; 
 the (related to the body function of living things) and money-based relationships are almost the same  although some limits/guidelines differ. Especially important for this topic is the higher level of total 
 risk disgust found among farmers in developing countries (Binswanger, 
 1980; Hamal and Anderson, 1982; Antle, 1987) compared to their partners in developed countries (Bond and Wonder, 1980; Poetsley and Harris, 
 1987; Myers, 1989). (These studies find almost the same  ranges for partial risk 
 disgust in developed and developing countries, and since incomes are lower 
 in developing countries this hints that they have higher total risk 
 disgust). Given what people believe now about pest control reducing risk 
 we would expect farmers in developing countries to adopt bug-killers with 
 excited interest (in something). However if the end/end result in this review is correct and bug-killers do not always reduce risk we should not be surprised if adoption of 
 bug-killers is no greater than for other inputs such as chemical (material that makes plants grow better)s. 
 Secondly, if information about pest density increases in value with 
 increasing risk disgust (as found by Antle 1988a, b), we would expect 
 bug-killers to be more acceptable to farmers in developing countries if they 
 are (helped increase/showed in a good way) as part of an IPM package involving scouting for pests before 
 making spray decisions. However, further work is needed in this area as 
 
 378 
 
 D.J. PANNELL 
 
 Thornton and Dent (1984a, b) found decreasing information value with 
 increasing risk disgust. 
 CONCLUSION 
 
 In the course of this review, some commonly made statements about the 
 influence of risk in pest control have been challenged. In addition some 
 gaps, unresolved issues and possible methodological shortages in the 
 existing books have been identified. 
 There are some sources of doubt which affect decision 
 making for pest control. It was decided that for some of these sources of 
 doubt (e.g. pest density, yield loss per pest, bug-killer effectiveness) 
 bug-killer use acts to reduce risk. However, for others (e.g. bug-killer 
 damage to crops, pest-free crop yield, output price) bug-killer use can 
 increase risk. This way the truth/trueness of the usual idea (you think is true) that bug-killers 
 reduce risk depends on the relative importance of these different sources of 
 doubt. This way it is important to think about  more sources of risk than the 
 ones most commonly carefully thought about/believed: doubt about pest density and pest 
 death. 
 It was noted that, due to (not going in a straight line)ities in the (related to the body function of living things) relationships, risk 
 can affect bug-killer decisions even if the farmer's goal is to (make as big as possible) 
 expected (money made/good thing received). (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) in the books points to/shows that the best level of 
 bug-killer use for risk-neutral decision makers is lower under doubt. 
 This issue has received attention relating to/connected to weeds but has been (compared to other things) 
 neglected for insects and sicknesses. On the other hand, applied studies of the 
 hit/effect of risk disgust on bug-killer decisions have been managed and did/done for 
 insects and sicknesses (although for a limited range of sources of doubt) but 
 not for weeds. 
 Information about the cropjpestjpesticide system not only increases 
 expected (money made/good things received) but can also be a very useful source of risk reduction in its 
 own right. On the other hand some studies have pointed to/showed that use of 
 information results in higher levels of risk. The hit/effect on risk of information use needs further (act of asking questions and trying to find the truth about something) to resolve this disagreeing (event(s) or object(s) that prove something). So 
 far, studies of information use in pest control<p><strong>NOTE: This document is incomplete. It was shortened to the maximum document length of 50,000 characters.</strong></p><div style="clear:both">&nbsp;</div>
